        <div class="paragraph">
                <h3>Improvements to Concept</h3>
                <p>
                    According to the exposure-effect theory people tend to be prefer things that are most familiar to them. Greater time spent on our application triggers customers to use the app automatically while they are at home. Encouraging the use of the online app during their offline experience is critical in ensuring the offline to online transition.
                </p>
        </div>
        <div class="paragraph">
                <h3>Key Takeaways for HEMA</h3>
                <p>
                        The use of the physical stores to promote its online goods is a valuable tool. It helps to build trust in HEMA’s brand. However, the high costs of real estate means that HEMA would have to create a more efficient in-store environment to respond to the increasing visitor numbers. Overcrowding could negatively affect customers’ experience of the store.<br/>
                        The use of an online payments system could help to reduce waiting times and improve revenue at the store. Also, it familiarises customers with the online payment environment of HEMA. This would make them more willing to buy groceries from HEMA even if they are not at the physical store.<br/>
                        Tracking of customers’ activities in the store via the application is also important in helping understand the tastes of Hema’s customers. Hema can then create tailored recipe recommendations for its customers and find out more ways in which it can satisfy its customers.<br/>
                </p>
